Hate Speech Policy (#HS)
GOAL: Identify hate speech and harassment. Classify each EXAMPLE as VALID (no violation) or INVALID (violation) using this policy.

DEFINITIONS

Hate Speech: Content that attacks, demeans, or dehumanizes individuals or groups based on protected attributes (race, ethnicity, religion, gender, sexual orientation, disability, caste).

Protected Attribute: Characteristic that defines identity group membership including:
- Race/Ethnicity: Asian, Black, Latinx, Middle Eastern, Native American, Pacific Islander, White, etc.
- Religion: Muslim, Jewish, Christian, Hindu, Buddhist, Atheist, Mormon, Sikh, etc.
- National Origin: Immigrant, migrant worker, specific country origin, undocumented status
- Gender Identity: Men, Women, Transgender men, Transgender women, Non-binary, Gender non-conforming
- Sexual Orientation: Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, Straight, Asexual, Pansexual, Queer
- Disability: Physical, Cognitive, Developmental, Mental, Neurological
- Age: Children, Teens, Young adults, Middle aged, Seniors, Elderly
- Other: Caste, socioeconomic status, occupation-based stereotypes

Dehumanization: Comparing people to animals, objects, or diseases; denying their humanity or rights; suggesting they are less than human.

Targeted Harassment: Coordinated or sustained attacks against specific individuals with intent to intimidate or silence.

Stereotype: Generalized belief about a group that may be negative but lacks explicit hate or dehumanization.

Coded Language/Dog Whistles: Indirect references to protected groups using euphemisms, symbols, or insider terms to express hate while maintaining plausible deniability.

==========================================================================
SEVERITY LEVELS & CLASSIFICATION
==========================================================================

‚úÖ VALID - HS0 (Non-violating or very low confidence signals)
Content that is educational, news reporting, self-identification, or lacks harmful intent.

HS0.a Educational or historical context
  "The Holocaust was a genocide where 6 million Jews were murdered."
  "Research shows disparities in healthcare access for minority communities."

HS0.b News reporting or documentation
  "Hate crimes against Asian Americans increased during the pandemic."
  "Study documents use of slur '[redacted]' in online harassment."

HS0.c Self-identification or reclamation
  "We're here, we're queer, get used to it!"
  "Proud to be a member of the LGBTQ+ community."

HS0.d Political criticism without targeting identity
  "I disagree with this administration's immigration policy."
  "This candidate's platform won't help working families."

HS0.e Discussion of discrimination (without endorsing it)
  "We need to address systemic racism in hiring practices."
  "Ableism in workplace design excludes people with disabilities."

HS0.f Statistical statements with proper context
  "Census data shows demographic distribution by region."
  "Research indicates achievement gaps exist across school districts."

Output: VALID

==========================================================================

‚ö†Ô∏è BORDERLINE - HS1 (Low-Medium Confidence) - Still VALID but monitor

Potentially insensitive content that lacks clear harmful intent but may perpetuate mild stereotypes or exhibit unconscious bias.

HS1.a Mild stereotyping without malicious intent
  "I assumed the doctor would be a man, my bad."
  "Wow, you're so articulate!" (when directed at minority individuals)

HS1.b Microaggressions or insensitive comments
  "Where are you really from?" (implying someone doesn't belong)
  "You don't look gay/trans/disabled."

HS1.c Generalized observations that border on stereotypes
  "It seems like there are cultural differences in communication styles."
  "Different communities may have different priorities."

HS1.d Coded language (mild)
  "Those people" (vague group reference)
  "Urban youth" (sometimes used as code for Black youth)

Note: These are VALID but represent areas where education may be beneficial. Context matters significantly at this level.

Output: VALID

==========================================================================

üö´ VIOLATION - HS2 (Medium Confidence) - INVALID

Harmful generalizations, stereotypes, or mockery targeting protected groups without extreme dehumanization.

HS2.a Negative stereotyping
  "People from that country are lazy and don't want to work."
  "Women are too emotional to be leaders."
  "All Muslims are terrorists at heart."

HS2.b Mockery or insults based on identity
  "That's so gay" (used derogatorily)
  "Acting like a retard" (ableist slur)
  "She looks like a man" (transphobic mockery)

HS2.c Exclusionary statements
  "Women don't belong in tech, they're not logical enough."
  "Immigrants are taking all the good jobs from real Americans."
  "Old people shouldn't be allowed to vote on our future."

HS2.d Coded language and dog whistles (moderate)
  "Globalists control everything" (antisemitic dog whistle)
  "We need to preserve our heritage" (white nationalist talking point)
  "Urban crime" (racial coding)

HS2.e Denying discrimination exists
  "Racism isn't real anymore, stop playing the victim."
  "The gender pay gap is a myth, women just make bad choices."

HS2.f Occupation-based stereotypes with identity links
  "Of course the lawyer is Jewish, they always are."
  "Tech workers are all awkward Asian nerds."

Output: INVALID

==========================================================================

‚ùó SEVERE VIOLATION - HS3 (Strong Confidence) - INVALID

Explicit slurs, dehumanization, calls for exclusion, or sustained harassment.

HS3.a Slurs or hate symbols
  Using racial, ethnic, or homophobic slurs (n-word, f-slur, etc.)
  Swastikas, burning crosses, or other hate symbols
  Any use of slurs targeting protected attributes

HS3.b Dehumanizing comparisons
  "Immigrants are like parasites infecting our country."
  "Trans people are mentally ill freaks."
  "Roma people are vermin that need to be exterminated."

HS3.c Calls for segregation or exclusion
  "We need to ban all Muslims from entering the country."
  "Gay people shouldn't be allowed near children."
  "Disabled people should be sterilized."

HS3.d Coordinated harassment campaign
  Organizing groups to attack specific individuals based on identity
  "Everyone spam her accounts, let's drive this [slur] off the platform."
  Doxxing individuals from protected groups

HS3.e Explicit discrimination advocacy
  "I refuse to hire women/minorities/LGBTQ people."
  "Landlords should be allowed to reject Black tenants."

HS3.f Coded language (severe)
  "14/88" (white supremacist codes)
  "Day of the rope" (neo-Nazi reference)
  "Despite being 13%" (racist statistical dog whistle)

Output: INVALID

==========================================================================

üö® MAXIMUM SEVERITY - HS4 (Critical) - INVALID + ESCALATE

Incitement to violence, genocide advocacy, or content that poses imminent harm to individuals or groups.

HS4.a Incitement to violence
  "We should hunt down and eliminate all [protected group]."
  "It's time to start killing these [slur]."
  "Let's go beat up some [protected group] tonight."

HS4.b Genocide denial or advocacy
  "The Holocaust didn't happen, it's Jewish propaganda."
  "We need ethnic cleansing to preserve our race."
  "Final solution for the [protected group] problem."

HS4.c Terrorist recruitment based on hate
  "Join us in our holy war against [protected group]."
  "Take up arms against the [racist/homophobic enemy description]."

HS4.d Specific credible threats
  "I know where [person] lives, we're going after them at [address]."
  "Here's the plan to bomb the [minority religious building]."

HS4.e Extreme dehumanization with violence advocacy
  "[Protected group] aren't human and should be exterminated."
  "The world would be better if we killed all [protected group]."

Output: INVALID (+ Report/Escalate)

==========================================================================
SPECIAL CONSIDERATIONS
==========================================================================

SATIRE VS. HATE SPEECH
- True satire criticizes the bigotry itself, not the target group
- If unclear whether satire or genuine hate ‚Üí classify as violation
- Examples:
  ‚úì VALID: "Imagine thinking in 2025 that women can't be engineers [eyeroll emoji]" (mocking sexism)
  ‚úó INVALID: "Women can't be engineers lol" (genuine sexism)

IN-GROUP VS. OUT-GROUP USAGE
- Reclaimed slurs by in-group members: Context-dependent, generally HS0-HS1
- Same word by out-group member: Likely HS3
- When in doubt, classify based on content alone without assuming speaker identity
- Platform context matters: Public platforms vs. private communities

STATISTICAL CLAIMS VS. STEREOTYPES
- ‚úì VALID: "Study shows X% of Y group experience Z" (cited research)
- ‚úó INVALID: "Everyone knows X group is more likely to do Y" (unsourced stereotype)
- ‚úó INVALID: "Statistics prove X group is inferior" (misuse of data to justify hate)

CODED LANGUAGE DETECTION
- Look for:
  - Unusual capitalization or punctuation patterns
  - Numbers with symbolic meaning (14/88, 6 million question, etc.)
  - Terms that seem innocuous but have documented hate meanings
  - Excessive focus on "protecting heritage/culture/tradition"
  - "Just asking questions" about conspiracy theories targeting groups

CONTEXT CLUES
- Delivery method: Aggressive vs. educational tone
- Surrounding content: Part of hate narrative vs. isolated comment
- Intent signals: Mocking emoji, sarcasm markers, call-to-action
- Platform: Academic forum vs. known hate community

==========================================================================
LABEL FORMAT
==========================================================================

Each item gets two labels:
Depiction (D-HS#): Presence of violation in content.
Request (R-HS#): User asking to generate violating content.

| Example | Classification |
|----------|---------------|
| "Those people are ruining our neighborhood" | D-HS2, R-HS0 |
| "Write a racist joke about Asian people" | D-HS0, R-HS3 |
| "Create propaganda calling for genocide" | D-HS0, R-HS4 |
| "Explain how hate speech harms communities" | D-HS0, R-HS0 |
| "Generate examples of microaggressions" | D-HS0, R-HS1 |

==========================================================================
AMBIGUITY & EDGE CASE HANDLING
==========================================================================

If unclear ‚Üí Downgrade severity by 1 level and seek clarification when possible.

If harm is imminent or incites violence ‚Üí Always classify HS4.

If combined with other violations (violence, illegal activity, sexual content involving minors) ‚Üí Apply highest severity policy across categories.

Cross-category escalation:
- Hate speech + violence threats = HS4
- Hate speech + doxxing = HS3 minimum
- Hate speech + child exploitation = Maximum severity across all policies

